RACE.RACE_TEXT: MAHONING VALLEY RACE COURSE RACE 1 1M Dirt CR: 33. Maiden Special Weight Purse 31800. FOR ACCREDITED OHIO BRED MAIDENS, THREE, FOUR, FIVE, AND SIX YEARS OLD. Three Year Olds, 124 lbs.; Older, 126 lbs.
RACE.FOOTNOTES: PRESSLEY RIDGE broke awkwardly to be a step slow from the gate, moved up the fence to stalk the pace down the backside, waited midway on the turn to angle five wide around the pacesetters and drew off down the lane when called upon as much the best. MY TICKET pressed the pace from two wide into the far turn, engaged the leader nearing the quarter pole with his rally, was no match for the winner and finished willingly as second best. WHY KENNY WHY set a well rate pace to the head of the lane and had no response when engaged turning for home. MY BUDDY MICAH was slow early to trail down the backside, made a mild rally through the turn and finished evenly without having been a threat. BALU dropped back entering the far turn and was outrun.

ENTRY.NAME: Pressley Ridge
ENTRY.COMMENT: awkward break, stalked pace, waited 5/16, swung 5w, much best

ENTRY.NAME: My Buddy Micah
ENTRY.COMMENT: slow early, mild bid, no threat,

RACE.RACE_TEXT: MAHONING VALLEY RACE COURSE RACE 2 1M Dirt CR: 69. Claiming Purse 17400. FOR REGISTERED OHIO BRED THREE YEAR OLDS AND UPWARD WHICH HAVE NOT WON TWO RACES SINCE MAY 8. Three Year Olds, 124 lbs.; Older, 126 lbs. Non-winners Of A Race Since October 8 Allowed 2 lbs. Claiming Price $6,500.
RACE.FOOTNOTES: SERENDIPITOUS set the pace for a half mile from the rail, was taken in hand off the lead into the turn to switch to the outside, rallied in the turn to take the lead, responded when challenged in upper stretch, briefly surrendered the lead in the lane and came again gamely to prevail. DEER CREEK ROAD unhurried for the first half mile to trail, circled four wide in the turn to engage the leader in upper stretch, briefly took the lead and was outkicked coming home while clearly second best. KARAMEL CORN prompted the early pace, dropped back in the field in the run down the backside and made a steady advance coming home to gain the show. ATTACK ANGLE pressed the pace for the first half, assumed command into the final bend, lacked a response when challenged turning for home and gave way through the stretch. HONOR THE D well placed to stalk the leaders to the far turn and faded. YOU'RE MY BOY BLUE slow early into the first turn, raced up the rail into contention on the first bend, dropped back down the backside and finished evenly as a non-threat.

ENTRY.NAME: Serendipitous
ENTRY.COMMENT: set pace, taken back, rallied, engaged, lost lead, came again

RACE.RACE_TEXT: MAHONING VALLEY RACE COURSE RACE 3 6F Dirt CR: 85. Claiming Purse 14900. FOR THREE YEAR OLDS AND UPWARD WHICH HAVE NEVER WON FOUR RACES. Three Year Olds, 124 lbs.; Older, 126 lbs. Non-winners Of A Race Since October 8 Allowed 2 lbs. Claiming Price $7,500 (Ohio Registered Foals Preferred).
RACE.FOOTNOTES: CRYO pressed the early pace from two wide, assumed command down the backside, opened a clear advantage through the turn and held sway in the lane while geared down. ONE MORE RING unhurried early to be near the rear of the field, commenced a rally in the turn, circled six wide turning for home and finished willingly with a steady advance. STRIKE A BEAT settled well off the pace to midway on the turn, rallied angling seven wide at the head of the lane and closed well to just miss the place. LUCKY SMILE bumped at the start, taken in hand to be reserved off the pace and made a late mild bid in the lane passing weakened rivals. NICHOLAS JAMES stalked the pace into the turn, made a three wide bid in the bend and flattened out turning for home. MY TWO AUNT JOANS tracked the pace from the fence in mid-pack and lacked a response when called upon. HINK'S PALADIN bumped rival leaving the gate, made an early bid from between horses in the turn and faded in the stretch. SMUDGE THE CAT well placed early and gave way coming home. MASTER rushed up the fence to take a brief lead early, pressed the pace to the turn and stopped.

ENTRY.NAME: Lucky Smile
ENTRY.COMMENT: bumped start, reserved, mild late bid, passed weaker

ENTRY.NAME: One More Ring
ENTRY.COMMENT: unhurried early, circled 6w, steady advance, willingly

ENTRY.NAME: Cryo
ENTRY.COMMENT: pressed pace, assumed command, drew clear, held safe

Non-winners Of A Race Since October 8 Allowed 2 lbs. Claiming Price $5,000 (Ohio Registered Foals Preferred).
RACE.FOOTNOTES: JONES FALLS prompted the pace to midway on the far turn, dueled with the pacesetter through the lane and pulled clear late in the drive. MR LAOBAN set the pace to the head of the lane, responded when challenged to deep stretch and was outkicked tp the wire while a clear second best. ALTAIR hopped at the start to trail early giving the field a couple lengths, rallied up the fence to a stalking position down the backside and flattened out nearing the quarter pole. DESERT HIGHWAY went one-paced throughout lacking a closing bid. GOOD SOUL reserved off the pace and lacked a response when called upon. FOGGY ALBION was never a threat. RAPA NUI was a non-factor.

Three Year Olds, 124 lbs.; Older, 126 lbs. Non-winners Of A Race Since October 8 Allowed 2 lbs. Claiming Price $10,000.
RACE.FOOTNOTES: MAYBE FRANKY set a well rated pace, responded when challenged on the final bend, shook clear turning for home, denied a stretch bid from the runner-up and finished convincingly. BIRDIE'S CHANTZ bobbled at the start, raced up to stalk the pace from between horses down the backside, rallied to loom in mid-stretch, failed to pass the winner and finished well to be best of rest. WAR MOON prompted the pace to the far turn, engaged the leader on the bend to threaten at the quarter pole and weakened in the lane. STATE OF GRACE unhurried early on to be well off the leaders and mounted a belated rally in the stretch. RUNAWAY BELLE slow early to be at the rear of the main body, circled wide when rallying in the turn and finished evenly. CARLY'S FLIGHT was the distant trailer down the backstretch and passed tiring rivals in the lane. I'M JAC'D tracked the leaders from four wide to the far turn and lacked a response when called upon. NANA ROZE was through early.

RACE.FOOTNOTES: PRIMITIVO prompted the pace down the backside, ranged up on the turn from between horses to challenge for the lead and pulled clear in the drive determinedly. STARS N SPACE set the pace through the turn, was engaged in a three-way battle at the head of the lane, was the first to be passed inside the eighth pole and re-rallied to gain the place in deep stretch in a game effort. TEQUILA FLATS stalked the pace down the backside, rallied three wide to loom boldly turning for home and was out-kicked in deep stretch. OVERLOAD well placed in the run down the backstretch, lost position through the turn and rallied belatedly in the lane. PECKS NOT BAD reserved off the pace to the top of the lane and showed late energy in the stretch. RED COMET rated off the leaders to the turn, rallied wide turning for home and made a mild bid in the drive. RED HOT POWER showed early foot to contend down the backstretch, was taken in hand into the turn to drop off the leaders and faded coming home. ROLLIN SO PERFECT was never a factor.

ENTRY.NAME: Tequila Flats
ENTRY.COMMENT: stalked pace, bid 3 wide, loomed, out-finished

ENTRY.COMMENT: early speed, in hand turn, faded

RACE.FOOTNOTES: LINE DANCER prompted the pace to the far turn, rallied two wide to engage the pacesetter turning for home, opened a clear lead in the lane and held the closer safe. MOBIL CHIC unhurried early to be at the rear of the main body to the far turn, rallied four wide in the final bend and made a steady advance to be second best. I'M LEGIT squeezed back at the start to be the trailer, continued to be the distant trailer to the final bend and rallied belatedly to close ground well through the stretch. SHAKEURSKINNYLEGS set a well rated pace through the far turn and failed to respond when challenged at the head of the lane. EARLY BLOOMER tracked the leaders from the rail down the backside, was set to an early drive on the turn and faded coming home. ABIGAIL LEE stalked the pace for a half mile and gave way.
